        <title>Evaluate Expressions-WE4-P2</title>
        <subsection>
            <title>Subgoals for evaluating an assignment statement</title>
            <xi:include href='./subgoals_evaluate_expressions.ptx' />
            <p>For the assignment statements below, either give the new value of the assigned variable, 
                or explain why the statement is invalid. Each problem is independent of the others 
                (e.g. Question 2 does not depend on Question 1, only the &#8220;Given&#8221; code). 
                <term>If you must round a numeric answer, use 4 decimal places of precision.</term></p>
        </subsection>
        <transition/>
        <subsection>
            <title>Expressions-WE4-P2</title>
            <p><term>Given</term></p>
            <program language="python"><input>
alpha = 2
beta = 1
delta = 3 
omega = 2.5
theta = -1.3
kappa = 3.0
            </input></program>
            <exercises>
                    <exercise>
                        <statement><p>Q27: lambda = alpha / kappa + delta<var/></p></statement>
                                <setup><var>
                                    <condition number="3.6667">
                                        <feedback><p>Correct</p></feedback>
                                    </condition>
                                    <condition string="^\s*x\s*$">
                                        <feedback><p>Incorrect</p></feedback>
                                    </condition>
                                </var></setup>
                    </exercise>
                    <exercise xml:id="m-Expr-WE4-P2-28">
                        <statement>
                            <p>Q28: eta = alpha * beta + (omega &#8211; theta) * kappa</p>
                            <p>Why is this statement invalid?</p>
                        </statement>
                        <choices>
                            <choice correct="yes">
                                <statement><p>cannot assign a float to an int variable</p></statement>
                                <feedback><p/></feedback>
                            </choice>
                            <choice>
                                <statement><p>eta does not have a value</p></statement>
                                <feedback><p/></feedback>
                            </choice>
                            <choice>
                                <statement><p>the value of eta cannot be changed</p></statement>
                                <feedback><p/></feedback>
                            </choice>
                            <choice>
                                <statement><p>cannot assign an int to a float variable</p></statement>
                                <feedback><p/></feedback>
                            </choice>
                    </choices>
                </exercise>
                <p><term>Given</term></p>
                <program language="python"><input>
r = 8
                </input></program>
                <exercise xml:id="m-Expr-WE4-P2-29">
                    <statement><p>Q29: Which statement will calculate the volume of a sphere most accurately?</p></statement>
                    <choices>
                        <choice>
                            <statement><p>volume = 4 / 3 * 3.14 * r * r * r</p></statement>
                            <feedback><p/></feedback>
                        </choice>
                        <choice>
                            <statement><p>volume = 4 / 3 * 3.14159 * r * r * r</p></statement>
                            <feedback><p/></feedback>
                        </choice>
                        <choice correct="yes">
                            <statement><p>volume = 4.0 / 3 * 3.14 * r * r * r</p></statement>
                            <feedback><p/></feedback>
                        </choice>
                        <choice>
                            <statement><p>An accurate result is not possible with these data types.</p></statement>
                            <feedback><p/></feedback>
                        </choice>
                    </choices>
                </exercise>
            </exercises>
        </subsection>
